# Final Tagless — cross-file trait inheritance with HKT (§3.3)

Exercises Phase 4 of v1.13: a user-defined algebra (`Logged[F]`)
extends a typeclass (`Monad`) imported from `std/functor-applicative-monad.ssc`.
The `extends` clause across file boundaries must resolve correctly and
inherited methods must be callable on the concrete instance.

[listMonad, optionMonad](std/functor-applicative-monad.ssc)

## Algebra extending an imported typeclass

```scalascript
trait Logged[F[_]] extends Monad[F]:
  def log(msg: String): F[String]
```

## Concrete instance for List

```scalascript
given listLogged: Logged[List] with
  def pure[A](a: A): List[A] = List(a)
  extension [A](fa: List[A])
    def map[B](f: A => B): List[B] = fa.map(f)
    def ap[B](ff: List[A => B]): List[B] =
      for { g <- ff; x <- fa } yield g(x)
    def flatMap[B](f: A => List[B]): List[B] = fa.flatMap(f)
  def log(msg: String): List[String] = List("[log] " + msg)
```

## Inherited `pure` and `flatMap` reachable via the concrete instance

```scalascript
val p: List[Int] = listLogged.pure(42)
println(p)
```

## `log` method — own method of the sub-algebra

```scalascript
val l: List[String] = listLogged.log("started")
println(l)
```

## Chained call using inherited pure + own log

```scalascript
val step1: List[String] = listLogged.log("step1")
val chained: List[String] = step1 ++ listLogged.log("step2")
println(chained)
```

## Concrete instance for Option

```scalascript
given optionLogged: Logged[Option] with
  def pure[A](a: A): Option[A] = Some(a)
  extension [A](fa: Option[A])
    def map[B](f: A => B): Option[B] = fa.map(f)
    def ap[B](ff: Option[A => B]): Option[B] = ff match
      case Some(g) => fa.map(g)
      case None    => None
    def flatMap[B](f: A => Option[B]): Option[B] = fa match
      case Some(a) => f(a)
      case None    => None
  def log(msg: String): Option[String] = Some("[log] " + msg)

val ol: Option[String] = optionLogged.log("option-step")
println(ol)
```
